<subSubSection lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="212" pageId="9" pageNumber="210" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,1842,2013]" lastBlockId="10.[151,1437,151,645]" lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="211" pageId="9" pageNumber="210">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1842,1868]" pageId="9" pageNumber="210">Description.</emphasis>
<typeStatus box="[352,456,1842,1868]" pageId="9" pageNumber="210">Holotype</typeStatus>
complete, with eight thoracic and 24 abdominal chaetigers. Body length 
<quantity box="[1275,1361,1842,1869]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" pageId="9" pageNumber="210" unit="mm" value="2.5">2.5 mm</quantity>
(branchial crown 
<quantity box="[288,377,1878,1905]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="9" pageNumber="210" unit="mm" value="1.5">1.5 mm</quantity>
); width 
<quantity box="[466,551,1878,1905]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="9" pageNumber="210" unit="mm" value="0.4">0.4 mm</quantity>
(
<tableCitation box="[565,647,1878,1904]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="29.[151,239,689,715]" captionText="TABLE 1. Comparative view of the main characters of the described Amphiglena species." pageId="9" pageNumber="210">Table 1</tableCitation>
). Body light brown coloured on ventral side and with a flattened abdomen (
<figureCitation box="[214,302,1914,1941]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1736,1760]" captionTargetBox="[154,1424,497,1706]" captionTargetId="figure-117@9.[151,1436,489,1712]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 6. Amphiglena pithecusensis sp. nov. A. entire worm, photo from the holotype; B. staining pattern; C. tip of the radiole; D. photo from anterior end, ventral view, material coloured with Shirlastain A; E. scheme of the anterior end ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4636143" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4636143/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="210">Fig. 6A</figureCitation>
). Crown with five pairs of radioles with 12 pairs of pinnules arranged in two longitudinal rows slightly alternating along the radiolar length. Gap between pinnules pairs decreasing along the radiole, with the first basal pair appearing slightly more separated from the others. Pinnules all of similar length, measuring about 1/4 of the total radiolar length, except first basal pair and the two distal pairs slightly shorter. Tip of radioles elongated, reaching almost 1/3 of the total radiolar length, thinning toward its blunt end (
<figureCitation box="[919,1007,187,214]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1736,1760]" captionTargetBox="[154,1424,497,1706]" captionTargetId="figure-117@9.[151,1436,489,1712]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 6. Amphiglena pithecusensis sp. nov. A. entire worm, photo from the holotype; B. staining pattern; C. tip of the radiole; D. photo from anterior end, ventral view, material coloured with Shirlastain A; E. scheme of the anterior end ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4636143" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4636143/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="211">Fig. 6C</figureCitation>
). Anterior peristomial ring not visible. Posterior peristomial ring higher ventrally with a well separated ventral incision and margins with an inflated appearance (
<figureCitation box="[265,384,259,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1736,1760]" captionTargetBox="[154,1424,497,1706]" captionTargetId="figure-117@9.[151,1436,489,1712]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 6. Amphiglena pithecusensis sp. nov. A. entire worm, photo from the holotype; B. staining pattern; C. tip of the radiole; D. photo from anterior end, ventral view, material coloured with Shirlastain A; E. scheme of the anterior end ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4636143" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4636143/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="211">Fig. 6D, E</figureCitation>
), connected to ventral basal flanges extending as prominent ridges from the peristomial ring to the base of ventral-most radiole. Peristomial eyes brown. Dorsal lips measuring 1/5 of the radiolar length. Pygidial eyes present as small clusters of red spots on lateral margins of pygidium. Thorax longer than wide. First thoracic chaetiger bearing only 2 chaetae similar in shape to superior chaetae of the following chaetigers. From the second to the eighth thoracic chaetiger, 7 uncini in each torus, with a short handle approximately 1/4 of the total uncinus length (0.31), with approximately four rows of teeth above main fang, and with rounded and flattened breast (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1937,1961]" captionTargetBox="[154,1433,680,1903]" captionTargetId="figure-276@10.[151,1436,669,1914]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 7. Amphiglena pithecusensis sp. nov. A. thoracic uncinus; B. companion chaeta; C. abdominal uncinus; D. superior thoracic chaeta; E. inferior thoracic chaeta; F. abdominal chaeta from a middle abdominal segment; G. abdominal chaeta from anterior abdominal segment." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4636147" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4636147/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="211">Fig. 7A</figureCitation>
). Companion chaetae present, with straight shaft and short mucro (
<figureCitation box="[934,1022,475,501]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1937,1961]" captionTargetBox="[154,1433,680,1903]" captionTargetId="figure-276@10.[151,1436,669,1914]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 7. Amphiglena pithecusensis sp. nov. A. thoracic uncinus; B. companion chaeta; C. abdominal uncinus; D. superior thoracic chaeta; E. inferior thoracic chaeta; F. abdominal chaeta from a middle abdominal segment; G. abdominal chaeta from anterior abdominal segment." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4636147" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4636147/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="211">Fig. 7B</figureCitation>
). Two superior broadly hooded chaetae (
<figureCitation box="[200,290,511,537]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1937,1961]" captionTargetBox="[154,1433,680,1903]" captionTargetId="figure-276@10.[151,1436,669,1914]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 7. Amphiglena pithecusensis sp. nov. A. thoracic uncinus; B. companion chaeta; C. abdominal uncinus; D. superior thoracic chaeta; E. inferior thoracic chaeta; F. abdominal chaeta from a middle abdominal segment; G. abdominal chaeta from anterior abdominal segment." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4636147" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4636147/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="211">Fig. 7D</figureCitation>
); 3 inferior paleate chaetae with short mucro as long as the paleate region (
<figureCitation box="[1138,1226,511,537]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1937,1961]" captionTargetBox="[154,1433,680,1903]" captionTargetId="figure-276@10.[151,1436,669,1914]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 7. Amphiglena pithecusensis sp. nov. A. thoracic uncinus; B. companion chaeta; C. abdominal uncinus; D. superior thoracic chaeta; E. inferior thoracic chaeta; F. abdominal chaeta from a middle abdominal segment; G. abdominal chaeta from anterior abdominal segment." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4636147" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4636147/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="211">Fig. 7E</figureCitation>
). Three abdominal uncini, with similar-sized small teeth above the main fang, with short-handle and appearing higher than long (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1937,1961]" captionTargetBox="[154,1433,680,1903]" captionTargetId="figure-276@10.[151,1436,669,1914]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 7. Amphiglena pithecusensis sp. nov. A. thoracic uncinus; B. companion chaeta; C. abdominal uncinus; D. superior thoracic chaeta; E. inferior thoracic chaeta; F. abdominal chaeta from a middle abdominal segment; G. abdominal chaeta from anterior abdominal segment." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4636147" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4636147/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="211">Fig. 7C</figureCitation>
). Two abdominal broadly hooded chaetae, similar, but longer, to the thoracic paleate chaetae both in anterior and median abdominal segments (
<figureCitation box="[485,603,619,645]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1937,1961]" captionTargetBox="[154,1433,680,1903]" captionTargetId="figure-276@10.[151,1436,669,1914]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 7. Amphiglena pithecusensis sp. nov. A. thoracic uncinus; B. companion chaeta; C. abdominal uncinus; D. superior thoracic chaeta; E. inferior thoracic chaeta; F. abdominal chaeta from a middle abdominal segment; G. abdominal chaeta from anterior abdominal segment." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4636147" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4636147/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="211">Fig. 7F, G</figureCitation>
). Spermathechae visible brown/red coloured.
</paragraph>
